<P><FONT FACE="AGaramond" SIZE=4><B>(a)</B> 
  <!-- On Tuesday, we expect to have a visit from Elizabeth Losh, author of the <a href="http://www.virtualpolitik.blogspot.com/">Virtualpolitik</a> blog and an expert in &quot;digital rhetoric&quot; (how we write effectively for electronic media). She will talk about Vannevar Bush, who predicted the Web decades ago in his classic article, &quot;<a href="http://www.theatlantic.com/doc/194507/bush">As We May Think</a>.&quot; He got some things wrong, too, and it will be interesting to talk about which predictions succeeded and which didn't.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT FACE="AGaramond" SIZE=4>For Tuesday's class, read the article. To focus your reading, consider the questions below. We're not asking you to write out answers and turn them in, but we do expect you to have answers in mind for Tuesday's class.</FONT><FONT FACE="AGaramond" SIZE=4>
</FONT></P>
<FONT FACE="AGaramond" SIZE=4>
<ol><li>What is the Memex?  What are its design features?  How is it similar and dissimilar to the networked personal computers of today?</li>
<li>What kind of user is Bush imagining?  In what situations does he describe the Memex being used?  (Business computing?  Recreational computing?  Social computing?  Archival storage?)</li>
<li>What kinds of input mechanisms are described by Bush?  (Think about all the devices he describes now, not just the Memex.)  What kinds of input mechanisms are not described?</li>
<li>What kinds of output mechanisms are described?</li>
<li>What does Bush say about the problem of natural languages?</li>
<li>How does Bush describe both paying for content and file-sharing between friends?  How does he justify this device economically?</li></ol></FONT>
